									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>I&#8217;m puzzled as to why the firefox developers concern themselves with the context so much.<br />
OpenGL was invented so that applications don&#8217;t have to care what video card is being used.</p>
<p>I know of the response &#8220;in theory, yes, but in practice…&#8221; and I&#8217;ll also reply to that in advance: for example, the KDE/plasma compositor has a menu that allows to choose OpenGL ES 2.0, OpenGL 3.1, OpenGL 3.3, OpenGL 4.5, etc.<br />
If there is a problem with the video card driver, let it be fixed there. The application is not the place to fix issues that do not stem from it!</p>
<p id="comment-like-15488" data-liked=comment-not-liked class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="https://mastransky.wordpress.com/2021/01/10/firefox-were-finally-getting-hw-acceleration-on-linux/?like_comment=15488&#038;_wpnonce=8385239050" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="151695875"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-15488" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p>
